definition.value: A class of quaternary ammonium chloride salts in which the nitrogen is substituted by a benzyl group, two methyl groups and an even-numbered alkyl chain.
A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of all three protons from antimonous acid.
An alkane-alpha,omega-diamine in which the alkane is ethane.
A bipyridine in which the two pyridine moieties are linked by a bond between positions C-2 and C-2'.
An alkane that is butane substituted by a methyl group at position 2.
An alkane that is propane substituted by a methyl group at position 2.
An iron-sulfur cluster is a unit comprising two or more iron atoms and bridging sulfur ligands.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is pentane with two carboxylic acid groups at positions C-1 and C-5.
Dicarboxylate anion of D-glucaric acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A glucaric acid anion that is the dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of glucaric acid.
A nucleoside triphosphate(4-) obtained by global deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of ATP; major species present at pH 7.3.
The L-enantiomer of homoserine lactone.
The D-enantiomer of homoserine lactone.
A  diether that is ethylene glycol in which the hydrogens of the hydroxy groups have been replaced by 2-[bis(carboxymethyl)amino]ethyl group respectively.
A monocarboxylic acid that is toluene in which one of the hydrogens of the methyl group has been replaced by a carboxy group.
A compound comprising a benzene ring core carrying a carboxylic acid substituent.

The simplest carboxylic acid, containing a single carbon. Occurs naturally in various sources including the venom of bee and ant stings, and is a useful organic synthetic reagent. Principally used as a preservative and antibacterial agent in livestock feed. Induces severe metabolic acidosis and ocular injury in human subjects.
An aminobenzoic acid in which the amino group is para to the carboxy group.
An aminobenzoic acid that is benzoic acid having a single amino substituent located at position 2. It is a metabolite produced in L-tryptophan-kynurenine pathway in the central nervous system.
A monohydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of salicylic acid.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is benzoic acid carrying a hydroxy substituent at C-4 of the benzene ring.
A short-chain saturated fatty acid comprising ethane attached to the carbon of a carboxy group.
A tricarboxylic acid that is propane-1,2,3-tricarboxylic acid bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 2. It is an important metabolite in the pathway of all aerobic organisms.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid that is butane in which one of the terminal methyl groups has been oxidised to a carboxy group.
A C6, straight-chain saturated fatty acid.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from one of the carboxy groups of succinic acid.
A C4-dicarboxylate that is the Z-isomer of but-2-enedioate(2-)
An optically active form of malic acid having (R)-configuration.
An optically active form of malic acid having (S)-configuration.
A C10, straight-chain saturated fatty acid.
The L-enantiomer of arabinose.
A hexaric acid resulting from formal oxidative ring cleavage of galactose.
An indol-3-yl carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of indole-3-acetic acid.
A compound in which a hydroxy group, -OH, is attached to a saturated carbon atom.
A tartaric acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-carboxy-2,3-dihydroxypropanoate.
Any member of a group of steroid carboxylic acids occuring in bile, where they are present as the sodium salts of their amides with glycine or taurine.
